{"id":"2211.16892","submitter":"Lilian Matthiesen","authors":"Lilian Matthiesen, Mengdi Wang","title":"Smooth numbers are orthogonal to nilsequences","comments":"72 pages","journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.NT","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Define an integer to be $[y',y]$-smooth if all of its prime factors belong to\nthe interval $[y',y]$. We identify suitable weights $g_{[y',y]}(n)$ for the\ncharacteristic function of $[y',y]$-smooth numbers that allow us to establish\nstrong asymptotic results on their distribution in short arithmetic\nprogressions. Building on these equidistribution properties, we show that (a\n$W$-tricked version of) the function $g_{[y',y]}(n) - 1$ is orthogonal to\nnilsequences. Removing small prime factors $p<y'$ and studying $[y',y]$-smooth\nnumbers instead of $y$-smooth numbers is integral to obtaining equidistribution\nin short arithmetic progressions when $y$ is small. Our results apply in the\nalmost optimal range $(\\log N)^{K} < y \\leq N$ of the smoothness parameter $y$,\nwhere $K \\geq 2$ is sufficiently large and for $y'<y^2$ of the shape $y' =\n(\\log N)^{K'}$.\n  As an application, we establish for any $y> N^{1/\\sqrt{\\log_9 N}}$ asymptotic\nresults on the number of solutions in $[y',y]$-smooth numbers to arbitrary\nfinite complexity systems of linear equations in the integers below $N$.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 30 Nov 2022 10:45:17 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-12-01"}
